<subSubSection pageId="59" pageNumber="60" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="59.[151,639,478,1137]" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[175,290,797,818]" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">Etymology.</emphasis>
This species is named for one of the enthusiastic supporters of this study and world renowned beetle specialist and musician, Richard “Blind Beetle” Leschen.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="59" pageNumber="60" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="59.[151,639,478,1137]" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[175,280,903,924]" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
This species can be distinguished from other species by the following combination of characters: small body 
<quantity box="[401,520,956,978]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.7999999999999998" metricValueMax="1.9" metricValueMin="1.7" pageId="59" pageNumber="60" unit="mm" value="1.7999999999999998" valueMax="1.9" valueMin="1.7">1.7–1.9 mm</quantity>
; frontal rostrum prominent; ventral surface of head weakly convex; eye large and prominent, approximately one-half length of temple; shape of antennomeres and genitalia unique to species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="59" pageNumber="60" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="59.[151,639,478,1137]" lastBlockId="59.[685,1173,194,826]" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[175,386,1089,1110]" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">Description of Male.</emphasis>
L e n g t h 
<quantity box="[492,608,1089,1111]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.7999999999999998" metricValueMax="1.9" metricValueMin="1.7" pageId="59" pageNumber="60" unit="m" value="1.7999999999999998" valueMax="1.9" valueMin="1.7">1.7– 1.9 m</quantity>
m. Body brown, antennae and maxillary palpi paler, elytra and legs paler (
<figureCitation box="[910,998,194,215]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="59.[175,207,1662,1681]" captionTargetBox="[162,637,1194,1640]" captionTargetId="figure-602@59.[151,637,1189,1647]" captionTargetPageId="59" captionText="Fig. 33. Sagola lescheni (lescheni species-group). a) Habitus, dorsal view; scale bar = 1 mm, b) Aedeagus, dorsal view; scale bar = 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4907829" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4907829/files/figure.png" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">Fig. 33a</figureCitation>
). 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1019,1082,194,215]" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">Head:</emphasis>
As long as wide, widest across eyes (
<figureCitation box="[990,1080,221,242]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="59.[175,207,1662,1681]" captionTargetBox="[162,637,1194,1640]" captionTargetId="figure-602@59.[151,637,1189,1647]" captionTargetPageId="59" captionText="Fig. 33. Sagola lescheni (lescheni species-group). a) Habitus, dorsal view; scale bar = 1 mm, b) Aedeagus, dorsal view; scale bar = 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4907829" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4907829/files/figure.png" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">Fig. 33a</figureCitation>
), ventral surface weakly convex with setose gular region. Antennomere 1 approximately 2 times longer than wide, 2–3 subquadrate, 4–5 longer than wide, 6–10 subquadrate. Frontal rostrum prominent. Frontal sulcus reaching midpoint of eye. Anterior frontal fovea oval, posterior frontal fovea round. Eye large and prominent, approximately one-half length of temple. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[862,944,433,454]" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">Thorax:</emphasis>
Prosternum as long as wide, widest at one-third length. Elytra rectangular (
<figureCitation box="[693,785,486,507]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="59.[175,207,1662,1681]" captionTargetBox="[162,637,1194,1640]" captionTargetId="figure-602@59.[151,637,1189,1647]" captionTargetPageId="59" captionText="Fig. 33. Sagola lescheni (lescheni species-group). a) Habitus, dorsal view; scale bar = 1 mm, b) Aedeagus, dorsal view; scale bar = 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4907829" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4907829/files/figure.png" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">Fig. 33a</figureCitation>
). Meso- and metathorax trapezoidal, longer than wide. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[862,970,513,534]" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">Abdomen:</emphasis>
Tergite IV with pair of transverse patches of microtrichia reaching middle. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[775,888,566,587]" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">Aedeagus:</emphasis>
Median lobe broader and longer than paramere (
<figureCitation box="[921,1013,593,614]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="59.[175,207,1662,1681]" captionTargetBox="[162,637,1194,1640]" captionTargetId="figure-602@59.[151,637,1189,1647]" captionTargetPageId="59" captionText="Fig. 33. Sagola lescheni (lescheni species-group). a) Habitus, dorsal view; scale bar = 1 mm, b) Aedeagus, dorsal view; scale bar = 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4907829" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4907829/files/figure.png" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">Fig. 33b</figureCitation>
). Phallobase of median lobe symmetrical and rounded (
<figureCitation box="[1075,1160,619,640]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="59.[175,207,1662,1681]" captionTargetBox="[162,637,1194,1640]" captionTargetId="figure-602@59.[151,637,1189,1647]" captionTargetPageId="59" captionText="Fig. 33. Sagola lescheni (lescheni species-group). a) Habitus, dorsal view; scale bar = 1 mm, b) Aedeagus, dorsal view; scale bar = 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4907829" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4907829/files/figure.png" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">Fig. 33b</figureCitation>
). Parameres symmetrical, elongate-triangular with setae apically (
<figureCitation box="[829,913,672,693]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="59.[175,207,1662,1681]" captionTargetBox="[162,637,1194,1640]" captionTargetId="figure-602@59.[151,637,1189,1647]" captionTargetPageId="59" captionText="Fig. 33. Sagola lescheni (lescheni species-group). a) Habitus, dorsal view; scale bar = 1 mm, b) Aedeagus, dorsal view; scale bar = 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4907829" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4907829/files/figure.png" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">Fig. 33b</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="59" pageNumber="60" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="59.[685,1173,194,826]" box="[709,1173,699,720]" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[709,837,699,720]" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">Distribution.</emphasis>
<collectingRegion box="[850,946,699,720]" country="New Zealand" name="Northland" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">Northland</collectingRegion>
(
<figureCitation box="[959,1030,699,720]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="63.[175,207,1662,1681]" captionTargetBox="[154,636,943,1636]" captionTargetId="figure-502@63.[151,637,938,1639]" captionTargetPageId="63" captionText="Fig. 36. Known collection localities of New Zealand Sagola species. S. lescheni: black circles; S. gourlayi: triangles; S. sharpi: black squares." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4907835" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4907835/files/figure.png" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">Fig. 36</figureCitation>
: black circles).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="59.[685,1173,194,826]" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[709,794,725,746]" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">Habitat.</emphasis>
Specimens of this species were collected using window and flight intercept traps or by sifting forest litter in hardwood and podocarp forests.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
